                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d142">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5393: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan (<persName
                            corresp="frus1932v03#p_GJC1" type="from">Grew</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-01T17:00:00+09:00"
                            >July 1, 1932—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 1—7:12 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>180. The best information which our Military Attaché has been able to compile
                    indicates that there are about 44,000 Japanese troops in Manchuria. In North
                    China aside from Manchuria the Japanese troops are reported to be 2,000. The War
                    Office admitted to the Military Attaché today that troops in North China are to
                    be increased in the near future. The strength of this increase is still
                    secret.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_GJC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
